<h1 align="center">xv6 Lottery Scheduler</h1>

<p align="center">
  A clean xv6-riscv implementation of lottery scheduling for CSE 321 Lab Assignment 2.
</p>

<p align="center">
  <b>Tickets</b> control CPU share.
  <b>Rounds</b> show scheduler selections.
  <b>settickets</b> lets user programs change priority.
</p>

---

## Project Overview

This repository replaces xv6's default round-robin scheduler with a lottery
scheduler. Each runnable process owns a number of tickets. At every scheduling
decision, xv6 draws a winning ticket and runs the process that owns it.

Processes with more tickets receive a larger share of CPU time over repeated
scheduling rounds.

## What Was Implemented

<div>
  <p><b>Process accounting</b><br>
  Every process now stores its ticket count and the number of scheduler rounds it has received.</p>

  <p><b>Ticket inheritance</b><br>
  Forked children inherit their parent's ticket count and start with zero rounds.</p>

  <p><b>New system call</b><br>
  User programs can call <code>settickets(int n)</code> to set their own ticket count.</p>

  <p><b>Lottery scheduler</b><br>
  <code>scheduler()</code> calculates total runnable tickets, draws a pseudorandom winner, and runs the selected process.</p>

  <p><b>Runtime visibility</b><br>
  <code>procdump()</code> now prints each process's rounds, so <code>Ctrl+P</code> can be used to observe scheduler behavior.</p>

  <p><b>User test program</b><br>
  <code>test_scheduler</code> creates long-running processes with configurable ticket counts.</p>
</div>

## Main Files

`kernel/proc.h` defines the new process fields.

`kernel/proc.c` contains the random generator, lottery scheduler, ticket
initialization, fork inheritance, round counting, and `procdump()` changes.

`kernel/sysproc.c`, `kernel/syscall.c`, `kernel/syscall.h`, `user/user.h`, and
`user/usys.pl` integrate the `settickets` system call.

`user/test_scheduler.c` is the assignment test program.

`SUBMISSION.md` contains the exact file-by-file modifications and full code
blocks required for submission.

## How To Test

Boot xv6:

```sh
make qemu
```

Run three test processes inside xv6:

```sh
test_scheduler 10 &
test_scheduler 5 &
test_scheduler 2 &
```

Press `Ctrl+P` after the processes have run for a short time. The process
rounds should grow approximately in the same ratio as their tickets: `10:5:2`.

## Expected Result

The output from `Ctrl+P` should show `test_scheduler` processes accumulating
different round counts. Exact values vary because lottery scheduling is
probabilistic, but higher-ticket processes should receive more rounds over time.

## Submission Reference

For grading or patch review, open `SUBMISSION.md`. It includes:

- exact modified files
- exact insertion points
- complete code blocks
- test commands
- expected behavior
- final requirement checklist

## Upstream xv6 Notes

xv6 is a re-implementation of Dennis Ritchie's and Ken Thompson's Unix
Version 6 (v6).  xv6 loosely follows the structure and style of v6,
but is implemented for a modern RISC-V multiprocessor using ANSI C.

ACKNOWLEDGMENTS

